subSubSection.paragraph:
BIOLOGY.
Usually the adults of 

P. agenor

are abundant before the beginning of the rainy season and are more active at night (
Ratcliffe 2003
). This species causes great damage to sugarcane. The adults of both sexes, but especially the males, perforate the stems and excavate burrows in the median and superior areas. They use the mandibles to burrow into the plant tissues, and the pronotal and head horns help to penetrate the stem (
Eberhard 1979
). The life cycle can last one year. The larva grows in the soil where it feeds on organic matter (
Eberhard 1979
; 
Mendonça 1996
). The pupa is also found in the soil. The larva develops for 4-8 months, and the pupa 2-3 months (
CENGICAÑA 2004
).
